<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="396" pageId="1" pageNumber="395" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1907,2039]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,154,682]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="396" pageId="1" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,1907,1931]" pageId="1" pageNumber="395">Description</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[347,412,1907,1931]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1692,1714]" captionTargetBox="[159,1416,179,1660]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,167,1672]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Adults. 1. Valeria wassalberti sp. n., holotype, Iran, prov. Hormozgan, 80 km N. of Bandar Abbas, slide GYP 5057 (coll. P. Gyulai); 2. Valeria carducha (Wiltshire, 1957), Iran, prov. Kermanshah, Zagros, slide GYP 5059 (coll. P. Gyulai)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3534838" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3534838/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="395">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity box="[551,631,1907,1931]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="395" unit="mm" value="27.0">27 mm</quantity>
. Eyes are semiglobular, black; palpi small, pale, with slight greyish suffusion, antennae filiform. Vesture of body and ground colour of the wings and the cilia is light greyish; more variegated suffused in the middle area and in the apex of forewings, but unicolorous in the hindwings. The most remarkable further external features of the new species are the rounded forewing apex, the typical, however obscure orbicular– reniform– and claviform stigmata, the dark definition of the spot between the orbicular and reniform stigmata, wavy antemedial lines, arched–crenate postmedial lines with fine white shade; conjectural, whitish subterminal lines, diffuse medial fascia and the hindwings with conspicuously defined discal spot. Underside of wings is whitish without wing pattern; only with the fine blackish shade of the discal spot.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">
The female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[442,513,298,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–5" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1416,179,1660]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,167,1672]" captionText="FIGURES 3–5. Female genitalia. 3. Valeria wassalberti sp. n., holotype, Iran, prov. Hormozgan, 80 km N. of Bandar Abbas, slide GYP 5057 (coll. P. Gyulai); 4. Valeria carducha (Wiltshire, 1957), Iran, prov. Kermanshah, Zagros, slide GYP 5059 (coll. P. Gyulai); 5. Valeria carducha (Wiltshire, 1957), Iran, prov. Khorassan, Kopeth Dagh, slide GYP 5058 (coll. P. Gyulai)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3613672" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3613672/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">Figs 3</figureCitation>
) can be characterized by the setosed papillae anales; medium long, fine apophyses anteriores and much longer apophyses posteriores; calycular, partly sclerotized antrum–ostium complex with V–shaped medial incision of the dorsal plate of ostium; tubular, narrow ductus bursae, of which the anterior section is more sclerotized, somewhat wrinkled, while posterior section is membranous, laterally positioned, fused with the terminal part of corpus bursae; prominent, semiglobular, apically strongly sclerotized appendix bursae with the presence of a strong oval sclerotization and large, elongate, elliptical–ovoid corpus bursae, without signa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,682]" box="[151,344,514,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">Male is unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="396" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,549,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">Distribution</emphasis>
. Only the 
<typeStatus box="[452,545,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">holotype</typeStatus>
is known, which was found in the southernmost 
<collectingCountry box="[1071,1117,550,573]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">Iran</collectingCountry>
, not very far from the Persian Gulf, in the early spring.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="396" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,622,646]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">Etymology</emphasis>
. The new species is named after Albert Wass (
<date box="[835,960,622,646]" pageId="2" pageNumber="396" value="1908" valueMax="1998">1908–1998</date>
), well–known Hungarian writer, died in the emigration in the 
<collectingCountry box="[340,397,658,682]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="396">USA</collectingCountry>
. Most of his historical novels deal with the tragic fate of the Szekely nation in Transylvania.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
